<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-911-972  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 911 972.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 27 1989 v6 n47 p13(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Docubase mixes text and graphics on 1 optical disk. (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sullivan, Kristina B.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Docubase Systems (product introduction).andO;Product:   Docubase (Data base management system) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware packagesWORMData base management systemsGraphics SoftwareText Data Bases.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Kristina B. SullivanandM;A Swiss firm is bringing to the U.S.andP;  market its WORM-based document storageand retrieval software that lets users integrate text files and images on asingle optical disk.andM;The Docubase software, available now from Docubase Systems of Geneva,provides a single system for incorporating scanned documents and images,mainframe database records, PC text files and 16-color PC-based graphicsimages, according to Peter Cloutier, marketing manager for Docubase, theSwiss subsidiary of Cegedim S.A., an IBM mainframe software developer basedin Paris.andM;Although other write once/ read many (WORM) document-storage systems supporteither scanned data, database records or PC text files, few support all threeinput sources, Cloutier claimed.andM;&quot;WORM technology has allowed the computer to handle long-term storage needs,&quot;and Docubase is well-suited to address those needs, Cloutier said.andM;Through user-defined templates, Docubase supports automatic indexing of PC ormainframe database reports, Cloutier explained.andP;  Each document, image,computer file or record is stored with an identification screen containing asmany as 41 subject words, including folder names, author, owner, destination,date and 32 key words.andP;  The software also provides nine zoom levels for anyscanned image or screen-captured image.andM;Docubase costs $8,995 for a single-user version and $19,995 for a four-userversion.andP;  The software can run on Novell Inc.'s NetWare, IBM's PC LAN andMicrosoft Corp.'s LAN Manager networks.andP;  It works with WORM disks withcapacities ranging from 400M bytes to 1.6 gigabytes from firms such as IBMand Ricoh Corp., and requires an AT-compatible computer and a hard disk.andM;Docubase can be reached in Geneva at 011-41-2243-1660 or through its publicrelations agency, Alliance Technology Inc. in Santa Clara, Calif., at (408)748-0293.andO;</TEXT></DOC>